article.description: Nicole Powell scored 28 points to lead Sacramento to an 86-82 victory in overtime against Washington on Sunday night.
article.headline: Monarchs need overtime to hold Mystics at bay
article.linkText: Monarchs hold off rallying Mystics in overtime
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Nicole Powell picked a great time to break out of her shooting slump. Powell scored 28 points, including seven in overtime, to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to an 86-82 victory over the Washington Mystics on Sunday night.
Down to the wire?
The battle for the final playoff spot in the East tightened up as the Mystics fell to within a half-game of the Liberty, who beat the Shock earlier Sunday.
Remaining games
Washington
New York
Tues. vs. Conn.Tues. at Chi.
Thurs. vs. N.Y.Thurs. at Wash.
Sun. at Conn.Fri. vs. Conn.
Averaging 12.5 points this season, Powell had totaled just 15 on 4-for-26 shooting in her last three games. Against the Mystics, she made five 3-pointers and all 11 free throws in helping the Monarchs snap a two-game losing streak despite playing without injured starters Yolanda Griffith and Ticha Penicheiro. "You can see the [shooting] stats, they were terrible. I just wanted to make something tonight," said Powell, who also had five rebounds and three steals. Kara Lawson scored 15 points, Rebekkah Brunson had 12 points and 10 rebounds, and Adrian Williams added 12 points in her second start for Sacramento (18-13). Plagued by turnovers and missed shots, the Monarchs' last eight points over the final 2:28 of overtime came on free throws. Alana Beard had 25 points for Washington (14-17), which lost its second straight after a four-game winning streak and had its lead cut to a half-game over New York for the fourth and final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. The Mystics host the Liberty on Thursday and also play second-place Connecticut twice this week. "It was a tough loss," Mystics forward DeLisha Milton-Jones said. "In my opinion it wasn't left up to the players. Some things could have been questioned. The refs saw something that we didn't. But we have three important games left and have to move on." Tamara James scored 17 points, Nakia Sanford had 15 points and 12 rebounds, and Milton-Jones added 11 points for Washington. Beard's 3-pointer pulled the Mystics to 83-82 with 5.5 seconds left in overtime. After taking a hard foul from behind, Scholanda Robinson converted one free throw and Powell made two more in the closing seconds to secure Sacramento's first overtime victory after losing its first three. "Finally we got an overtime win," said Robinson, whose eight points were all on free throws. "We try to let things go, we weren't thinking about the other overtime losses. This team has a lot of confidence in itself, no matter who is playing." The third-place Monarchs trail West-leading Phoenix by 2½ games, and face the Mercury twice and second-place San Antonio once in the final week. "To win against a team like Washington that is playing so well right now without our two leaders was huge," Monarchs coach Jenny Boucek said. "We had players who aren't even used to playing that were making big plays. Good teams find a way to win." Washington rallied from an 11-point deficit in the second half and sent the game into overtime when Monique Currie made one of two free throws with 3.2 seconds to tie the game at 73. The Mystics are now 3-1 in overtime games. "When we got to overtime we felt the game was ours," Milton-Jones said. "This was a dog fight, a prelude to the playoffs. Even though they didn't have Yo [Griffith] and Ticha, Sacramento is a championship team with a lot of depth. No matter who plays for them they always play well."
